von willebrand factor antigen and ac
von_willebrand_factor.Why_Get_Tested: To help determine the cause of unexplained excessive or repeated episodes of bleeding, to diagnose von Willebrand disease (VWD), and to distinguish between different types of VWD
von_willebrand_factor.When_To_Get_Tested: When you have a personal or family history of heavy, prolonged, and/or spontaneous bleeding; when your healthcare provider suspects that you may have a bleeding disorder
von_willebrand_factor.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm

name: Semen Analysis
Seminal Fluid Analysis
Sperm Analysis
Sperm Count
semen_analysis.Why_Get_Tested: As part of infertility testing if your partner is having trouble becoming pregnant or after a vasectomy to determine if the operation was successful
semen_analysis.When_To_Get_Tested: When you think you might have a fertility problem or about three months after you have had a vasectomy
semen_analysis.Sample_Required: A semen sample collected in a sterile, wide-mouth container provided by the lab; often collected on-site, but sometimes it may be collected at home using a special condom obtained from a healthcare practitioner. For infertility testing, the sample must be analyzed within one hour of collection. Two separate collections on two separate days may be required.
semen_analysis.Test_Preparation_Needed: For infertility testing, refrain from having sex or masturbation for 2-5 days before sample collection; carefully follow instructions provided.

name: Serum Transferrin Receptors
Soluble Transferrin Receptor
sTfR
TfR
Transferrin Receptor
soluble_transferrin_receptor.Why_Get_Tested: To detect iron deficiency anemia and distinguish it from anemia caused by chronic illness or inflammation
soluble_transferrin_receptor.When_To_Get_Tested: When iron deficiency anemia is suspected
soluble_transferrin_receptor.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm

name: Serum Urate
UA
Uric Acid
uric_acid.Why_Get_Tested: To detect high levels of uric acid in the blood, which could be a sign of the condition gout, or to monitor uric acid levels when undergoing chemotherapy or radiation treatment; to detect high levels of uric acid in the urine in order to diagnose the cause of kidney stones and to monitor those with gout who are at risk of developing such stones
uric_acid.When_To_Get_Tested: When you have joint pain or other symptoms that your healthcare practitioner suspects may be due to gout; when you have had or are going to have certain chemotherapy or radiation therapies for cancer; when you have recurrent kidney stones; when you have gout or are otherwise at risk for kidney stone formation
uric_acid.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in the arm or a 24-hour urine sample
uric_acid.Test_Preparation_Needed: None may be needed; however, some institutions recommend fasting. Follow any instructions you are given.

name: Sex Hormone Binding Globulin
Sex Hormone Binding Globulin (SHBG)
TeBG
Testosterone-estrogen Binding Globulin
sex_hormone_binding_globulin_shbg.Why_Get_Tested: Most commonly measured in the evaluation of low testosterone (androgen deficiency) in men; also commonly used in the evaluation of women with signs and symptoms of excess male hormones (androgens)
sex_hormone_binding_globulin_shbg.When_To_Get_Tested: When you have signs and symptoms of increased or decreased testosterone and aÂ total testosterone measurement is inconsistent with your symptoms
sex_hormone_binding_globulin_shbg.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm

name: SMRP
Soluble Mesothelin-Related Peptides
soluble_mesothelin_related_peptides.Why_Get_Tested: To monitor progression or recurrence of a rare cancer called mesothelioma that affects the membranes that surround the lungs, heart, and abdominal cavity; most cases of mesothelioma are associated with asbestos exposure.
soluble_mesothelin_related_peptides.When_To_Get_Tested: After you have been diagnosed with mesothelioma, this test may be ordered anytime during or after treatment to follow response to treatment.
soluble_mesothelin_related_peptides.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm

name: T-cell Gene Clonality
T-Cell Receptor Gene Rearrangement
TCGR
TCR Gene Rearrangement
t_cell_receptor_gene_rearrangement.Why_Get_Tested: To help diagnose a T-cell lymphoma; sometimes to detect and evaluate residual lymphoma cells
t_cell_receptor_gene_rearrangement.When_To_Get_Tested: When a healthcare practitioner thinks that you may have a T-cell lymphoma; when a healthcare practitioner would like to assess whether treatment has been effective and/or whether lymphoma has recurred
t_cell_receptor_gene_rearrangement.Sample_Required: A bone marrow, tissue such as a lymph node (biopsy), or body fluid sample; sometimes a blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm

name: T. vaginalis
Trichomonas Testing
Trichomonas vaginalis testing
Wet Prep
trichomonas_testing.Why_Get_Tested: To diagnose an infection with the parasite Trichomonas vaginalis, which causes the sexually transmitted disease trichomoniasis
trichomonas_testing.When_To_Get_Tested: When a woman has symptoms of infection, such as a foul-smelling vaginal discharge, genital itching, and/or pain during urination, or when a man has genital itching or irritation, burning after urination or ejaculation, and/or a discharge from the penis
trichomonas_testing.Sample_Required: For men or women, the initial portion of urine stream (first-catch urine sample); or in women, a swab of fluid and cells from the vagina or cervix; or in men, a swab from the tube that carries urine from the bladder to outside the body (urethra).

name: Tg
TGB
Thyroglobulin
Thyroglobulin, Serum or Plasma
thyroglobulin.Why_Get_Tested: To monitor treatment of thyroid cancer and to detect recurrence; less commonly, to help determine the cause of hyperthyroidismÂ and hypothyroidism
thyroglobulin.When_To_Get_Tested: Prior to and after the completion of treatment for thyroid cancer, before and after radioactive iodine therapy, and at regular intervals to monitor for recurrence; it may be ordered in conjunction with other thyroid tests for certain thyroid disorders.
thyroglobulin.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm
thyroglobulin.Test_Preparation_Needed:
Usually none; however, depending on the laboratory method used for measurement of thyroglobulin, some dietary supplements such as multivitamins or supplements rich in vitamin B7 (Biotin) should not be taken at least 12 hours before the test is performed in order to avoid any test interference that may lead to false results.
Based on information provided by the lab, your healthcare practitioner should inform you if this or any other preparation is necessary.

name: TG
TRIG
Triglycerides
triglycerides.Why_Get_Tested: To assess your risk of developing heart disease; to monitor effectiveness of lipid-lowering therapy
triglycerides.When_To_Get_Tested:
Screening: as part of a lipid profile during a regular medical exam at least once every four to six years for adults; for children, at least once between the ages of 9 and 11 and again between the ages of 17 and 21
Monitoring: may be done more frequently if you have risk factors for heart disease and/or if you are being treated for unhealthy lipid levels
triglycerides.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm or from a fingerstick
triglycerides.Test_Preparation_Needed: Current standards recommend that testing be done when you are fasting. For 9 to 12 hours before the test, only water is permitted. In addition, alcohol should not be consumed for 24 hours just before the test. Your healthcare practitioner may decide that you may be tested without fasting. Follow any instructions you are given and tell the person drawing your blood whether or not you have fasted.

name: Thiopurine methyltransferase (TPMT)

TPMT Phenotype

thiopurine_methyltransferase_tpmt.Why_Get_Tested: To detect a thiopurine methyltransferase (TPMT) deficiency and determine your risk of developing severe side effects if treated with the class of immune-suppressing thiopurine drugs that includes azathioprine, mercaptopurine, and thioguanine
thiopurine_methyltransferase_tpmt.When_To_Get_Tested: Typically, prior to thiopurine drug treatment; this is a specialized test and is not routinely ordered.
thiopurine_methyltransferase_tpmt.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm or a swab from inside your cheek (i.e., buccal swab)
thiopurine_methyltransferase_tpmt.Test_Preparation_Needed: For measuring TPMT enzyme activity (TPMT phenotyping), the test must be performed prior to taking a thiopurine drug since it may affect results; for the genetic test (TPMT genotyping), no specific test preparation is needed.

name: Thrombin Clotting Time
Thrombin Time
TT
thrombin_time.Why_Get_Tested: As part of an investigation of excessive bleeding or inappropriate blood clot formation (thrombotic episode), particularly to evaluate the level and function of fibrinogen; to detect heparin contamination
thrombin_time.When_To_Get_Tested: When you have bleeding or thrombotic episodes, or recurrent miscarriages; when a PT and/or PTT test is prolonged, particularly if abnormal fibrinogen level or function is considered; when heparin contamination of a blood sample is suspected
thrombin_time.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm

name: Thyroid Function Panel
Thyroid Panel
thyroid_panel.Why_Get_Tested: To help evaluate thyroid gland function and to help diagnose thyroid disorders
thyroid_panel.When_To_Get_Tested: When you have signs and symptoms suggestingÂ hypo- or hyperthyroidism due to a condition affecting the thyroid
thyroid_panel.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm
thyroid_panel.Test_Preparation_Needed: None needed; however, certain medications can interfere with the tests included in the panel, so tell your health practitioner about any drugs that you are taking.

name: Thyroid-stimulating Hormone (TSH)
Thyrotropin
thyroid_stimulating_hormone_tsh.Why_Get_Tested: To help diagnose thyroid disorders and to monitor treatment of hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism; sometimes a TSH test is used to screen newborns for congenital hypothyroidism; there is no consensus within the medical community as to whether screening of adults should be done.
thyroid_stimulating_hormone_tsh.When_To_Get_Tested: When you have signs and symptoms of hyperthyroidism or hypothyroidism and/or an enlarged thyroid (goiter) or when you have a thyroid nodule (a small lump on the thyroid gland that may be solid or a fluid-filledÂ cyst); when you are being treated for a thyroid disorder
thyroid_stimulating_hormone_tsh.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm or from pricking the heel of an infant
thyroid_stimulating_hormone_tsh.Test_Preparation_Needed: No test preparation is needed. However, certain medications, multivitamins and supplements can interfere with the TSH test, so tell your healthcare practitioner about any prescribed or over-the-counter drugs and/or supplements that you are taking. If you take thyroid hormone as treatment for thyroid disease, it is recommended that your blood sample be drawn before you take your dose for that day. Acute illness may affect TSH test results. It is generally recommended that thyroid testing be avoided in hospitalized patients or deferred until after a person has recovered from an acute illness.

name: TORCH
TORCH Panel
TORCH Test
torch.Why_Get_Tested: To detect certain infectious diseases that can cause birth defects in a newborn; sometimes to screen pregnant women for these infections
torch.When_To_Get_Tested: When a baby is born with congenital abnormalities that may be caused by an infection with one of the diseases included in the panel; sometimes if a woman is exposed to certain infections or becomes ill while pregnant
torch.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in the woman's arm by needle or by heelstick for infants

toxoplasmosis_testing.Why_Get_Tested: To detect a Toxoplasma gondii infection in a pregnant woman, unborn baby, or in aÂ person with a weakened immune system (immunocompromised) who has flu-like symptoms; sometimes to determine if a person has been previously infected or to help determine if complications are due to an active Toxoplasma infection
toxoplasmosis_testing.When_To_Get_Tested: When a pregnant woman or a person with a weakened immune system has been exposed to T. gondii and/or has flu-like symptoms or a severe eye or brain infection that a health practitioner suspects are due to toxoplasmosis
toxoplasmosis_testing.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm; sometimes a cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) or amniotic fluid sample

name: Urinalysis
Urine Analysis
Urine Test
urinalysis.Why_Get_Tested: To screen for, help diagnose and/or monitor several diseases and conditions, such as kidney disorders or urinary tract infections (UTIs)
urinalysis.When_To_Get_Tested: When you have symptoms, such as abdominal pain, back pain, frequent or painful urination; sometimes as part of a health examination, pregnancy check-up, hospital admission, or pre-surgical work-up
urinalysis.Sample_Required: One to two ounces of urineâ€”a sufficient sample is required for accurate results; sometimes you may be directed to collect a sample using a "clean-catch" technique: women should spread the labia of the vagina and clean from front to back; men should wipe the tip of the penis. Start to urinate, let some urine fall into the toilet, then collect one to two ounces of urine in the container provided, then void the rest into the toilet.

name: Vancomycin
vancomycin.Why_Get_Tested: To measure and monitor the level of vancomycin in your blood
vancomycin.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm
vancomycin.Test_Preparation_Needed: None, but timing of the sample for testing is important; samples are typically collected just before the next dose (trough level). Follow any instructions provided.

name: Vanillylmandelic Acid (VMA)
Vanillylmandelic Acid, urine
VMAU
vanillylmandelic_acid_vma.Why_Get_Tested: To help diagnose or rule out a neuroblastomaÂ or other neuroendocrine tumor; to monitor the effectiveness of treatment
vanillylmandelic_acid_vma.When_To_Get_Tested: When your child has a lump in the abdomen (abdominal mass), bruising around the eyes, trouble walking, or bone pain; when you have symptoms of increased catecholamine release, such as persistent or periodic high blood pressure, severe headaches, rapid heart rate, and sweating; when you have been treated for a neuroendocrine tumor, such as neuroblastoma
vanillylmandelic_acid_vma.Sample_Required: A 24-hour urine sample is preferred; sometimes a random urine sample is acceptable.
vanillylmandelic_acid_vma.Test_Preparation_Needed: This test is affected by caffeine, certain foods, certain drugs, and stresses. Inform your healthcare practitioner of any medications you are taking and follow any instructions you are given for things to avoid before sample collection.

name: Very Low-Density Lipoprotein Cholesterol
VLDL
VLDL Cholesterol
VLDL-C
vldl_cholesterol.Why_Get_Tested: To help assess the risk of developing heart disease
vldl_cholesterol.When_To_Get_Tested: As part of a lipid profile during a regular medical exam (at least once every 4-6 years for adults; for children, at least once between the ages of 9 and 11 and again between the ages of 17 and 21); more frequently if you have risk factors for heart disease
vldl_cholesterol.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm or a fingerstick
vldl_cholesterol.Test_Preparation_Needed: Current standards recommend that testing be done when you are fasting. For 9 to 12 hours before the test, only water is permitted. In addition, alcohol should not be consumed for 24 hours just before the test. Your healthcare practitioner may decide that you may be tested without fasting. Follow any instructions you are given and tell the person drawing your blood whether or not you have fasted.

west_nile_virus_testing.Why_Get_Tested: To help diagnose an infection caused by West Nile virus (WNV); to determine the cause of viral meningitis or encephalitisÂ or febrile illness that occurs during the summer season; to detect the presence of WNV and to track its spread in the community and across the United States; to screen for WNV in donated units of blood, tissues, or organs
west_nile_virus_testing.When_To_Get_Tested: When you have symptoms suggesting WNV such as headache, fever, stiff neck, and muscular weakness and have been exposed to mosquitos or when you have had a diagnosis of encephalitis and/or meningitis associated with the summer season
west_nile_virus_testing.Sample_Required: Cerebrospinal fluid collected from a spinal tap and/or a blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm

name: Zika Antibody Test
Zika PRNT
Zika RT-PCR Test
Zika Virus Testing
zika_virus_testing.Why_Get_Tested: To diagnose a Zika virus infection
zika_virus_testing.When_To_Get_Tested: When you develop a fever, rash, joint pain, and conjunctivitis (pink eye) after traveling to an area where Zika virus is endemic or have symptoms and had sexual contact with someone who recently traveled from an area where Zika is present; if you are pregnant and have traveled to an area where Zika is active, regardless of symptoms; or when a baby is born with microcephaly (small head)
zika_virus_testing.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm and/or a urine sample collected in a clean container; less commonly cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) or amniotic fluid

ZPP/Heme Ratio
zinc_protoporphyrin.Why_Get_Tested: To screen for and monitor chronic exposure to lead in adults; to detect iron deficiency in children
zinc_protoporphyrin.When_To_Get_Tested: When you have been chronically exposed to lead, as part of a program to monitor lead exposure, and/or when your healthcare provider suspects lead poisoning; as part of a screening program for iron deficiency in children and adolescents
zinc_protoporphyrin.Sample_Required: A blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm or from a fingerstick
